setNameString

public void setNameString(java.lang.String n)
                   throws DmcValueException
Description copied from class: DmcObjectName
Implementing classes must overload this method to initialize their name properly with the String form of their name. This can basically be seen as implying that you must have a constructor for your name implementation that takes a String as argument. We need setNameString() so that we can create DmcTypeNamedObjectREF values based on a String.

valuesAreEqual

public boolean valuesAreEqual(DmcMappedAttributeIF obj)
Description copied from interface: DmcMappedAttributeIF
This method is used by the Modifier mechanism to determine whether or not a change has occurred as a result of applying the modifier. Having this method forces you to implement a value comparison function, as opposed to relying on you to remember to overload the equals method on your values. When the value is put in the map, we get back the existing value if the key already existed. The add() method will then call this function to determine if a change really took place; if this method returns false, we report the change (by passing back the new value), otherwise we return null from the add().

You should ensure that you compare both the key and the value in your comparison.

Specified by:
valuesAreEqual in interface DmcMappedAttributeIF
Parameters:
obj - Another mapped attribute.
Returns:
true if the value of this attribute matches the value of the object passed in and false otherwise.
